27
00:01:08.045 --> 00:01:10.495
Emergency management comes in four parts, reduction,

28
00:01:10.495 --> 00:01:14.745
readiness, response and recovery, excuse me.

29
00:01:15.405 --> 00:01:16.665
And day-to-day community facing

30
00:01:16.695 --> 00:01:18.105
work reduction and readiness matter.

31
00:01:18.105 --> 00:01:20.665
Most, they cost much less than response and recovery,

32
00:01:21.365 --> 00:01:23.625
and they build resilience before disaster strikes.

33
00:01:24.565 --> 00:01:26.305
But the builders that wait to these two areas,

34
00:01:26.965 --> 00:01:28.905
it leans heavily towards response and recovery.

35
00:01:29.535 --> 00:01:31.265
That misses a chance to prevent the

36
00:01:31.265 --> 00:01:32.425
very outcomes that that drove.

37
00:01:32.425 --> 00:01:34.865
This reform readiness only works

38
00:01:34.865 --> 00:01:35.905
when expectations are clear.

39
00:01:35.995 --> 00:01:38.585
Plans are tests that in capability can be shown in practice.

40
00:01:39.135 --> 00:01:41.545
High level plans on the shelf do not build resilience.

41
00:01:42.725 --> 00:01:45.745
If the, if the system keeps valuing documents over local

42
00:01:46.065 --> 00:01:49.025
preparedness, we may stay stuck in response mode.

43
00:01:49.395 --> 00:01:51.825
We'll keep reacting instead of reducing risk before it hits.

44
00:01:52.885 --> 00:01:54.745
If Parliament wants reduction in readiness in the form

45
00:01:54.745 --> 00:01:56.745
of the in front of the system, the law

46
00:01:56.745 --> 00:01:59.465
and its regulations must set out miserable expectations.

47
